			<h3 class="comments-title">
			14 thoughts on &ldquo;<span>Computer Vision research</span>&rdquo;		</h3>

		<ol class="commentlist">
				<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="li-comment-883">
		<article id="comment-883" class="comment">
			<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/dc97328c3ad890da0ec6bc1f2072a26b?s=44&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/dc97328c3ad890da0ec6bc1f2072a26b?s=88&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' /><cite class="fn"><a href='http://www.smashingdir.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Chet</a> </cite><a href="https://ngs.ics.uci.edu/computer-vision-research/#comment-883"><time pubdate datetime="2007-01-30T07:25:33+00:00">January 30, 2007 at 7:25 am</time></a>			</header><!-- .comment-meta -->

			
			<section class="comment-content comment">
				<p>Now that developers have the ability to apply different styles for different vision types, the Web has opened up. you can apply &#8220;print&#8221; or &#8220;screen&#8221; or other types of visual styles for different types of mediums. One popular fad going around in web development is to give users a choice of a high-contrast view of the website vs. the normal stylized view. The high-contrast version increases font, and makes all colors extremely contrast from each other making for maximum visibility.</p>
							</section><!-- .comment-content -->

